What Floats Your Boat?

Amaka ODOGWU, Evangelos-Pavlo ROUSOS, Dmitry STAKHANOV, Veena VISWANATHAN, and Tavor YISRAEL

The example that we are going to work on is the case study Boats written by Jorg Niessing and Theodoros Evgeniou both professors at INSEAD. The business model is defined for a boating company that is looking to expand in North America and needs to understand the requirements of their current and potential client base so that they can better serve them and provide boats that are more targeted and hence more sellable. To do this, they decided to segment the market using quantitative market segmentation with the use of factor and cluster analysis.

To make this determination, the company has asked more than 3000 current and potential customers to complete a questionnaire consisting of 29 questions about their preferences towards boating. The questions are listed at the end of this section. Using a scale of 1-5, the company was thus able to gather significant data on the market situation and direction. However the responses turned out to be overlapping and hard to manage in size. It was thus decided to use factor analysis and reduce them into a few meaningful sets. Let us consider for example the following attributes in evaluating a customer:

  1. When buying a boat, I do a lot of shopping around and visit multiple dealers
  2. When buying a boat, getting the lowest price is more important than the boat brand
  3. The brand of boat I buy says a lot about who I am
  4. I only consider buying a boat from a reputable brand
  5. I am willing to pay a premium for a brand with a reputation for high quality
  6. Owning a boat is a way of rewarding myself for my hard work
  7. Owning a boat gives me a sense of achievement
  8. When buying a boat, functionality is more important than style
  9. I see my boat as a status symbol
  10. When buying a boat, I rely more on expert opinion than my own (e.g. consumer reports, salespeople)
  11. I tend to perform minor boat repairs and maintenance on my own
  12. When it comes to boating, I tend to prefer a basic boat with little to no frills
  13. When buying a boat, I tend to buy the latest and greatest
  14. When buying accessories for my boat, I tend to buy the latest and greates
  15. I am serious about the technology on my boat
  16. People tend to come to me for advice about boating
  17. I consider myself more knowledgeable about boating than the rest of my boating peers
  18. Boating gives me a feeling of adventure
  19. Boating allows me to experience nature
  20. When not on my boat, I often find myself doing boating related activities
  21. Boating helps me escape from everyday life and relax
  22. Boating helps me stay active
  23. Boating allows me to excel in the sports that I am passionate about (e.g. fishing, racing, water sports)
  24. Boating gives me an outlet to socialize with family and/or friends
  25. Being in charge of my boat is very important to me
  26. Having a powerful boat is what is most important to me
  27. Boating is the number one thing I do with my spare time
  28. Boating is my true passion in life
  29. Boating is one of many things I do in my spare time

Survey respondents gave a rating of one to five based on their agreement with the statements.

Boarding the Boat

Based on the attributes and data received from the survey, we need to identify several attributes that would fundamentally describe the attitudes of the customer segments and use these further in the segmentation process. However, eyeballing and manually grouping 29 different attributes is not an easy task. Does this data capture some 'derived attributes' that may have a meaning?

Intuitively it may seem that the data above captures three fundamental groups of boaters:

  1. Luxury Boaters
  2. Price-Conscious Boaters
  3. Boating Enthusiasts

In order to decide which segment to target in building boats, they would then need to ask the following questions:

  1. Are you a luxury boater?
  2. How price-conscious are you?
  3. How much do you enjoy boating?

Asking these questions would not yield very much as this would lead to very noisy and misleading answers: the questions are fluffy and not easy to answer. So instead of asking these 'naive' questions, Creeqboat is using raw attributes/data like the ones above, which can also be gathered easier. The idea then is to see how this data can be 'translated' in meaningful derived attributes that, for example, could capture the 'equivalent answers' one could get if one were to ask directly the two naive questions above - or possibly other such 'complex' questions.

Using factor analysis is a simpler way to arrive at a smaller number of factors or derived attributes that help explain the data, which is the goal of this report.

Our Process for Dimensionality Reduction

To perform the analysis outlined above, we will use the following system of analysis:

Steps of Our Factor Analysis

  1. Confirm the data in metric

  2. Decide whether to scale or standardize the data

  3. Check the correlation matrix to see if Factor Analysis makes sense

  4. Develop a scree plot and decide on the number of factors to be derived

  5. Interpret the factors and consider factor rotations

  6. Save factor scores for subsequent analyses

Step 1: Getting on the Metric System

Steps 1-3 are about specific descriptive characteristics of the data. In particular, the methods we consider require that the data are metric (step 1): this means not only that all data are numbers, but also that the numbers have an actual numerical meaning, that is 1 is less than 2 which is less than 3 etc.

The data we used have the following descriptive statistics:

Step 2: Does Size Really Matter?

This data are all are on the same scale so there is no issue. Having some variables with a very different range/scale can often create problems: most of the “results” may be driven by a few large values, more so that we would like. To avoid such issues, one has to consider whether or not to standardize the data by making some of the initial raw attributes have, for example, mean 0 and standard deviation 1, or scaling them between 0 and 1. Here is for example the R code for the first approach, if we want to standardize all attributes:

ProjectDatafactor_scaled = apply(ProjectDataFactor, 2, function(r) {
    if (sd(r) != 0) 
        res = (r - mean(r))/sd(r) else res = 0 * r
    res
})

Below are the summary statistics of the scaled dataset:

Step 3: Entering the (Correlation) Matrix

Our factor analysis will group together highly correlated raw attributes. This will make a few new variables (factors) that are hopefuly explained by a unifying cause, are easier to manage, and easier to communicate and make decisions based on.

Error: object 'tags' not found

The starting point of factor analysis is a correlation matrix, in which the intercorrelations among the variables are presented. The dimensionality of this matrix can be reduced by looking for variables that highly correlate with a group of other variables but correlate badly with variables outside of that cluster. There are quite a few large (in absolute value) correlations. These clusters of variables with high intercorrelations can measure a factor. But how should they be grouped? With what weights should we combine these raw attributes in groups? They can be grouped by different factors driven by quality concerns (Q2 and Q12), brand (Q9 and Q3) and wiliness to pay (Q13 and Q14). Let's now see what factor analysis suggests as factors.

This make-up is very unlcear and does not provide very distinct categories, which was the original goal. To improve the distribution of attributes the factor analysis can undergo 'rotation'. If the raw attributes are highly correlated or interdependent then they can be compressed into factors then rotate to select the few key eliments of the factors.

A number of factors can be selected based on a variety of criterion, and these rotated factors become the new dataset.

Each factor has an eigenvalue and a percentage of the varience that it explains. These values and judgment determine how many factors will be included. For the factors we have generated the eigenvalues and the varience (as well as the commulative variencce) are as follows:

The first factor always has the highest eigenvalue. One method of selection for factors is to exclude all factors with eigenvalues less than 1. In our analysis that would leave us with the first five factors.

Another method of selection is to determine the cummulative amount of varience you want to explain. Each factor in this analysis explains very little individually, escpecially after the first few. We experiemented with demanding that 70% of the varience be explained by the selected factors, and that yeilded 12 factors. When examining what these factors represented, however, we were disastisfied. They appeared to segement the market across two different dimmesions: How one relates to their boats, and how one purchases a boat. One person could easily fall into either category, and it is much more useful for a buisiness to know the combination. Knowing that some people use their boats to socialize and some people boat for relaxation and that some people compare price and others compare features does not help a business design their strategy very much. It is much more helpful to know how the end goal of owning a boat relates to the method of purchase. For this reason we decided to be satisfied with a much smaller explained varience and felt that between four and six factors were appropriate.

Another method of analysis is the scree plot, which graphically shows how much of the outcome can be explained by each of the factors:

abline

The 'elbow' of the plot where there is a sharp decline in the rate of change in the eigenvalue is the point at which further eigenvalues are excluded. In this case that value appears to be six.

Based on the three criteria (eigenvalue > 1, cumulative percentage of variance explained, and the elbow of the scree plot), and using our current selection criterion, namely eigenvalue, since we rejected the outcome of using varience, for this data we can decide to use 5 components only.

5. But What Does It Mean?

These five selected factors are still challenging to understand. It is hard to translate them into meaningful information as is, and a technique that can help improve their readability and relevance is rotation.

The rotated factors will each include only the most meaningful attributes, and there won't be cross-over between the attributes used in different factors.

For our data, the 5 selected factors look as follows after the varimax rotation:

We now can replace our original data with the new ones and continue our analysis. For example, we can now visualize our original data using only the newly derived attributes. Here is the plot when we use only the top 2 factors:

Data Visualization Using the top 2 Derived Attributes (Factors)

So What Floats Your Boat?

Taking eigenvalue as the selection criterion and a minimum variance threshold of 65, we have 5 selected factors. The factor analysis and the subsequent rotation of the factors allows us to interpret the data and obtain the following segmentation.

  1. The Compensation Boater A typical customer in this segment is wealthy, flashy, and sees his boat as a symbol of his achievement and social standing in society. Therefore, this segment is generally less price sensitive than the others and is willing to fork out some serious cash for his boat to ensure (a) his boat is the most powerful in the market and is technologically more advanced than the rest (b) the brand is of the highest quality and © people around him are aware that his boat possess the said features. A subset of this segment is the passionate boater, who spends most of his spare time on boating related activities and prides himself as being a source of information and advice for boating.

The single most important attribute of this group is “I see my boat as a status symbol”

  1. The Yacht Club Enthusiast The customers in this segment enjoy boating as an adventurous hobby and view it as an escape from their humdrum daily routines. The typical customer has usually purchased his boat with his own money which is a source of pride and sense of achievement, and uses it as a means to socialize with family and friends.

The single most important attribute of this group is tied between “Boating helps me escape everyday life and relax” and “Boating gives me a feeling of adventure”

  1. The Boat Geek Such customers are serious about the brand they own, as long as it is perceived as being of the highest quality, and insist on having the best technology on their boats. They appear more concerned about the outward appearance of their boats rather that the functions and features they possess.

The single most important attribute of this group is “I only consider buying a boat from a reputable brand”

  1. The Expert This segment consists of customers who consider themselves very knowledgeable about boats and take pride in being a source of information and advice for other boating enthusiasts. These customers know the workings of a boat and typically make minor repairs and maintenance on their own, this adding to their sense of being a veritable repository of boating information.

The single most important attribute of this group is “I tend to perform minor boat repairs and maintenance on my own”

  1. The Practical Boat Owner Function takes precedence over style for this segment of customers. The average customer is very price sensitive and is unconcerned about the brand of the boat as long as it has the basic features the customer deems necessary to operate.

The single most important attribute of this group is “When buying a boat getting the lowest price is more important than the boat brand”
